  "prompt": "Do Go-Back-N ARQ and Selective Repeat ARQ use cumulative acknowledgements or an acknowledgement for every individual packet?",
  "response": "Go-Back-N ARQ and Selective Repeat ARQ handle acknowledgments differently based on their design for reliability and efficiency in data transmission:\n\n1. **Go-Back-N ARQ:**\n   - **Cumulative Acknowledgments:** This protocol uses cumulative acknowledgments. When the receiver sends an acknowledgment for a specific packet, it implicitly acknowledges that all previous packets have been received correctly up to that point.\n   - **Behavior:** If a packet is lost or an error is detected, the sender will retransmit that packet and all subsequent packets in the window, even if some of them were received correctly.\n\n2. **Selective Repeat ARQ:**\n   - **Individual Acknowledgments:** Unlike Go-Back-N, Selective Repeat sends individual acknowledgments for each correctly received packet. This allows the receiver to acknowledge each packet separately, regardless of the order in which they arrive.\n   - **Behavior:** If a packet is lost or corrupted, only that specific packet is retransmitted, rather than all subsequent packets. This approach is more efficient, especially in environments where packet loss is common, as it reduces unnecessary retransmissions.\n\n**Summary:**\n- **Go-Back-N ARQ** uses **cumulative acknowledgments**, acknowledging the highest sequence number received in order.\n- **Selective Repeat ARQ** uses **individual acknowledgments** for each packet, allowing for more precise retransmissions.\n\nThis distinction allows Selective Repeat to be more efficient in scenarios with higher error rates, while Go-Back-N is simpler and may be suitable for environments with lower error rates.\n\n**References:**\n- Andrew S. Tanenbaum, *Computer Networks*\n- W. Richard Stevens, *TCP/IP Illustrated*\n\n**Example Illustration:**\n\n- **Go-Back-N:** If packets 1, 2, 3 are sent and packet 2 is lost, the receiver sends an ACK for packet 1. The sender then retransmits packets 2, 3, etc.\n  \n- **Selective Repeat:** If packets 1, 2, 3 are sent and packet 2 is lost, the receiver can acknowledge packets 1 and 3 individually (ACK for 1 and ACK for 3). The sender only retransmits packet 2.\n\n---\n\n**In summary:**\n\n\u2022 Go-Back-N employs cumulative acknowledgments, while\n\u2022 Selective Repeat sends acknowledgments for each individual packet.",
